<!--
    The server.xml file is a core configuration file for declarative vert.x, dictating how the server behaves
    during startup and operation. This file defines various elements like the server, services, connectors, 
    and containers, which handle requests and manage web applications.

    <server-config>
    ...
    </server-config>
-->

<!--- Server configuration -->
<!ELEMENT server-config (allowed-headers|server-opts|tcp-opts|network-opts|http-opts|allowed-methods|keystore-config|truststore-config|routing-config|context-root|access-log|security-constraint)*>

<!--- Web server configuration parameters -->
<!ELEMENT server-opts (ssl|host|port|accept-backlog|client-auth|sni|use-proxy-protocol|proxy-protocol-timeout|register-write-handler)*>

<!--- 
    Set the ssl parameter if you want your server to be started in ssl mode.
    Along with this you have to use a keystore containing the SSL certificate and private key. 
    You also need to ensure the server is listening on the HTTPS port.
-->
<!ELEMENT ssl (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The host setting that determines which network interface the server will listen on. 
    By default, the server listens on all available network interfaces (typically 0.0.0.0), 
    but you can configure it to listen on a specific host.
-->
<!ELEMENT host (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The port attribute, of type int, specifies the TCP port number that the server will 
    listen for incoming connections. By default, if not specified, Vert.x will choose the
    defautl port as 8080.
-->
<!ELEMENT port (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It specifies the maximum number of pending connection requests that the server can queue
    before refusing new connections. It's essentially a limit on the number of incomplete TCP 
    connections that the server will allow to accumulate. A higher acceptBacklog allows the 
    server to handle more concurrent connection attempts, but setting it too high can lead to 
    resource exhaustion if the server isn't processing connections quickly enough.
-->
<!ELEMENT accept-backlog (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Configures the engine to require/request client authentication. The accepted values are:

    1. NONE - No client authentication is requested or required.
    2. REQUEST - Accept authentication if presented by client. If this option is set and the client chooses
    not to provide authentication information about itself, the negotiations will continue.
    3. REQUIRED - Require client to present authentication, if not presented then negotiations will be declined.
-->
<!ELEMENT client-auth (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The setting for Server Name Indication (SNI).
    SNI is a TLS extension that allows a client to specify which hostname it is trying to connect 
    to when using HTTPS. This is crucial for hosting multiple HTTPS sites on the same IP address
    and port.
    You can enable or disable SNI support for the HTTP server. When set to true, the server will 
    attempt to use SNI to determine the correct certificate to present to the client during the 
    TLS handshake.
-->
<!ELEMENT sni (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    To use the proxy protocol with a Vert.x HttpServer, you need to enable it by setting this property. 
    This allows the server to correctly interpret the PROXY protocol header, which is often used in 
    proxy setups like HAProxy to pass client connection information to the backend server.
-->
<!ELEMENT use-proxy-protocol (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It specifies the maximum time, in seconds, that the server will wait for a PROXY protocol header
    from a client before considering the connection timed out. The default value for this timeout is 10 seconds.
-->
<!ELEMENT proxy-protocol-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This is used to configure whether write handlers for server WebSockets should be registered by default.
    It doesn't directly relate to HTTP server options for general requests, but rather specifically to
    WebSocket connections. Setting this option to true will cause a write handler to be registered 
    automatically for all WebSocket connections created by the server.
-->
<!ELEMENT register-write-handler (#PCDATA)>

<!--- TCP Option parameters -->
<!ELEMENT tcp-opts (tcp-no-delay|tcp-keep-alive|so-linger|idle-timeout|read-idle-timeout|write-idle-timeout|tcp-fast-open|tcp-cork|tcp-quick-ack|tcp-user-timeout|ssl-opts)*>

<!---
    It controls whether the TCP_NODELAY socket option is enabled for the HTTP server. 
    When enabled (set to true), it disables the Nagle's algorithm, potentially reducing latency for small 
    packets at the cost of increased network overhead. When disabled (set to false), the Nagle's algorithm
    is enabled, potentially improving network efficiency for many small packets. 
    The default value is false.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-no-delay (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This refers to the underlying TCP connection's keep-alive mechanism. It periodically sends probes 
    to ensure the connection is still active and prevent it from being closed by intermediate 
    network devices due to inactivity.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-keep-alive (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls the socket's linger behavior when closing the connection. Specifically, it determines 
    how long the socket waits to send any remaining unsent data before actually closing the connection.
-->
<!ELEMENT so-linger (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This setting determines how long an HTTP connection can be idle before it's automatically closed.
    This setting helps prevent resource exhaustion by actively disconnecting connections that are not
    actively sending or receiving data.
-->
<!ELEMENT idle-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It determines the maximum time a server socket will remain idle (without receiving any data) before
    the connection is automatically closed. It's a mechanism to prevent idle connections from consuming
    resources indefinitely.
-->
<!ELEMENT read-idle-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It sets the maximum amount of time a connection can remain idle before being closed due to inactivity
    on the write side. It's a crucial setting for preventing idle connections from consuming resources 
    indefinitely.
-->
<!ELEMENT write-idle-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Enable the TCP_FASTOPEN option - only with linux native transport.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-fast-open (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This option, when enabled, leverages the TCP_CORK option available in Linux native transports.
    This option, when set to true, instructs the kernel to delay sending TCP packets until a larger 
    buffer is filled, or a timeout is reached. This can improve network performance in certain scenarios 
    by reducing the number of small packets sent.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-cork (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows the server to send TCP acknowledgments (ACKs) immediately, rather than waiting for 
    the kernel's delayed ACK timer. This can improve network performance, particularly in scenarios
    with frequent small packets.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-quick-ack (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls the maximum time a TCP connection can be idle before being closed by the server. 
    This is particularly useful for preventing resource exhaustion from inactive connections.
-->
<!ELEMENT tcp-user-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    SSL Options for tcp
-->
<!ELEMENT ssl-opts (ssl-handshake-timeout|key-cert-options|trust-options|enabled-cipher-suites|crl-paths|crl-values|use-alpn|enabled-secure-transport-protocols)*>

<!---
    It allows you to set a timeout for the SSL/TLS handshake process. This timeout defines how long 
    the system will wait for a client to complete the handshake before considering it a failure.
-->
<!ELEMENT ssl-handshake-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    This options are used within SSLOptions to configure the key and certificate information 
    for SSL/TLS connections. Specifically, KeyCertOptions define how the server or client presents 
    its identity during the SSL handshake. You'll typically use KeyStoreOptions or PemKeyCertOptions 
    as implementations of KeyCertOptions to provide the necessary certificate and key data, 
    usually in a keystore file or PEM format.
-->
<!ELEMENT key-cert-options (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    This options are used to configure how the SSL/TLS layer trusts certificates during a connection. 
    They specify the source of trusted certificates, which can be a keystore, a set of certificates, 
    or a trust manager.
-->
<!ELEMENT trust-options (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    This property, when not empty, determines which cipher suites are used for encryption during 
    the SSL/TLS handshake. It overrides the default cipher suites provided by the SSL engine.
-->
<!ELEMENT enabled-cipher-suites (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    It controls whether or not the Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension for 
    TLS is enabled. ALPN allows the client and server to negotiate which application-level protocol 
    (like HTTP/2) to use over the secure connection.
-->
<!ELEMENT use-alpn (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    It is used to specify the paths to Certificate Revocation List (CRL) files. These files are 
    used to verify if a certificate presented by a server or client has been revoked, enhancing 
    the security of SSL/TLS connections.
-->
<!ELEMENT crl-paths (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    It allows you to add a CRL value (represented as a Buffer) to the SSL options, enabling CRL 
    checking during SSL/TLS handshakes.
-->
<!ELEMENT crl-values (#PCDATA)>

<!---
    It sets up the ssl transport protocols that are to be enabled for the current vertx server.
-->
<!ELEMENT enabled-secure-transport-protocols (#PCDATA)>


<!--- Network options for the http server -->
<!ELEMENT network-opts (send-buffer-size|receive-buffer-size|reuse-address|traffic-class|log-activity|reuse-port)*>

<!--- 
    It controls the size of the TCP send buffer used by the HTTP server. This buffer is used to 
    temporarily store data before it's sent over the network. Setting it appropriately can impact 
    performance, especially under high load or when dealing with large responses.
-->
<!ELEMENT send-buffer-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls the size of the TCP receive buffer for the server. This buffer is used to store 
    incoming data before it's processed by the Vert.x HTTP server. Setting a larger buffer size 
    can potentially improve performance under high load, while a smaller buffer might be more 
    appropriate for lower traffic scenarios.
-->
<!ELEMENT receive-buffer-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls whether a socket can be bound to an address that is already in use, allowing multiple 
    sockets to listen on the same port. When enabled, it allows a new server instance to start even 
    if a previous server instance on the same address is still in a TIME_WAIT state, which can occur 
    after a server shuts down.
-->
<!ELEMENT reuse-address (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to set the traffic class (also known as "service class" or "DiffServ octet") for the 
    underlying TCP sockets of an HTTP server. This option is related to the IP header's DSCP or ECN fields, 
    which can be used to prioritize network traffic.
-->
<!ELEMENT traffic-class (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It enables logging of network activity for an HTTP server. When set to true, Netty's pipeline is 
    configured to log network events at the DEBUG level on Netty's logger. To see these logs, you must
    also configure your logging framework (e.g., Logback, SLF4J) to enable DEBUG level logging for 
    io.netty.handler.logging.LoggingHandler.
-->
<!ELEMENT log-activity (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to enable or disable the reuse of the port for the HTTP server. When reusePort is 
    set to true, the server will attempt to reuse the port even if it's in a TIME_WAIT state, which 
    can be useful in certain scenarios like when restarting the server quickly after it was previously 
    closed.
-->
<!ELEMENT reuse-port (#PCDATA)>

<!--- Http option parameters -->
<!ELEMENT http-opts (per-message-web-socket-compression-supported|max-header-size|compression-supported|compression-level|max-web-socket-frame-size|max-web-socket-message-size|handle-100-continue-automatically|per-frame-web-socket-compression-supported|max-chunk-size|http2-clear-text-enabled|register-web-socket-write-handlers|alpn-versions|http2-rst-flood-window-duration|accept-unmasked-frames|web-socket-preferred-client-no-context|max-initial-line-length|initial-settings|http2-rst-flood-max-rst-frame-per-window|max-form-attribute-size|web-socket-allow-server-no-context|web-socket-closing-timeout|web-socket-compression-level|tracing-policy|http2-connection-window-size|max-form-fields|decompression-supported|max-form-buffered-bytes|decoder-initial-buffer-size)*>

<!--- 
    This allows the server to compress responses using gzip or deflate when a client indicates support
    for these methods in the Accept-Encoding header.
-->
<!ELEMENT compression-supported (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This option  controls the level of compression used when the server compresses response bodies. 
    This setting, ranging from 1 to 9, affects the trade-off between compression ratio and CPU usage. 
    A higher level (closer to 9) provides better compression but consumes more CPU resources. 
    The default value is 6, which is a common balance point.
-->
<!ELEMENT compression-level (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures the maximum allowable size of a WebSocket frame in bytes. It defaults to 65536 (64KB).
    You can increase this limit. This setting prevents denial-of-service attacks by limiting the size 
    of individual WebSocket messages.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-web-socket-frame-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures the maximum allowable size for a WebSocket message, including fragmented messages. 
    The default value is 4 times the DEFAULT_MAX_WEBSOCKET_FRAME_SIZE which is 65536, meaning the 
    default max message size is 262144 bytes (4 * 65536).
-->
<!ELEMENT max-web-socket-message-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    To enable automatic handling of the "Expect: 100-Continue" header in Vert.x, you need to set this
    option to true. This tells the Vert.x HTTP server to automatically respond with a "100 Continue"
    (HTTP 1.1) or "102 Processing" (HTTP/2) status code when a client sends an "Expect: 100-Continue" 
    header, indicating that it is safe to send the request body.
-->
<!ELEMENT handle-100-continue-automatically (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It limits the maximum size of HTTP chunks received by the server. It's a safety mechanism to prevent 
    excessively large chunks from overwhelming the server. The default value is 8192 bytes.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-chunk-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It sets the maximum allowed length for the initial line of an HTTP request (e.g., 
    "GET /index.html HTTP/1.1"). This setting helps prevent denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by limiting
    the size of incoming request lines. The default value is 4096 bytes.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-initial-line-length (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It defines the maximum allowed size in bytes for HTTP headers (including the initial line) when a
    server receives an HTTP request. Setting this option prevents large or malicious header sizes 
    from overwhelming the server.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-header-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures the maximum allowed size for a single attribute in a form submission. It's a 
    mechanism to prevent excessive memory consumption from overly large form field values. The default 
    value for maxFormAttributeSize is 8192 bytes. If a form attribute exceeds this limit, the server 
    will typically respond with an HTTP status code 413 (Request Entity Too Large).
-->
<!ELEMENT max-form-attribute-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to set the maximum number of fields allowed in a form when handling HTTP requests. 
    This setting is crucial for preventing denial-of-service (DoS) attacks where malicious clients 
    might send excessively large forms to overwhelm the server. By setting a reasonable limit, 
    you can mitigate such risks.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-form-fields (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It limits the amount of buffered bytes when decoding a form. This setting prevents excessive 
    memory consumption by restricting the size of form data the server will buffer during request 
    processing. The default value is 1024 bytes.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-form-buffered-bytes (#PCDATA)>

<!--- The initial settings for an http option. -->
<!ELEMENT initial-settings (header-table-size|push-enabled|max-concurrent-streams|initial-window-size|max-frame-size|max-header-list-size)*>

<!--- Put your DTDDoc comment here. -->
<!ELEMENT header-table-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls whether the server supports HTTP/2 server push. If enabled, the server can 
    proactively send resources to the client in anticipation of future requests, potentially 
    improving performance, especially for static assets.
-->
<!ELEMENT push-enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It sets the limit on the number of concurrent streams an HTTP/2 server allows for a single 
    connection. This setting is crucial for managing resources and preventing denial-of-service 
    (DoS) attacks, especially in HTTP/2 where multiplexing is common.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-concurrent-streams (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This Setting controls the initial flow control window size for HTTP/2 connections. This setting, 
    which is an integer value, determines how much data a server can send before needing to wait
    for an acknowledgement from the client. Setting it to a larger value can improve throughput, 
    especially for large responses, while a smaller value can help prevent a slow client from 
    overwhelming the server. The default value is -1.
-->
<!ELEMENT initial-window-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It refers to the maximum allowed size for a single WebSocket frame, not the overall message 
    size which can be composed of multiple frames. The default max-frame-size for WebSocket frames
    is 65536 bytes (64KB). If a larger frame is received, a CorruptedFrameException is thrown.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-frame-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures the maximum allowed size for the combined size of all HTTP headers in a request. 
    This setting helps prevent denial-of-service attacks by limiting the amount of memory that 
    can be consumed by a single request.
-->
<!ELEMENT max-header-list-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to configure the ALPN (Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation) versions for an
    HTTP/2 server. ALPN is a TLS extension that allows the server and client to negotiate which 
    protocol (e.g., HTTP/1.1, HTTP/2) to use during the initial connection handshake. 
    The alpnVersions option in HttpServerOptions enables you to specify the supported protocol 
    versions that the server will advertise to clients.
-->
<!ELEMENT alpn-versions EMPTY>

<!--- 
    To enable HTTP/2 clear-text (h2c) support in Vert.x HttpServerOptions, you need to set this
    option to true. This allows the server to negotiate HTTP/2 without requiring TLS.
-->
<!ELEMENT http2-clear-text-enabled (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to configure various settings for an HTTP/2 server, including the connection 
    window size. The http2ConnectionWindowSize setting controls the initial flow control window 
    size for an HTTP/2 connection. This setting determines how much data the server can send to 
    a client before waiting for the client to acknowledge receipt of the data.
-->
<!ELEMENT http2-connection-window-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to enable decompression for incoming requests. The attribute controls whether 
    the server will automatically decompress request bodies that are compressed using gzip, 
    deflate, or br (Brotli) encodings. By default, decompression is enabled.
-->
<!ELEMENT decompression-supported (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to configure whether the server accepts unmasked WebSocket frames. Setting 
    this attribute to true enables the server to accept WebSocket frames that are not masked 
    (i.e., have a mask key of all zeros). By default, Vert.x WebSocket servers will reject 
    unmasked frames, as per RFC 6455, Section 5.1, which mandates masking for client-to-server 
    frames.
-->
<!ELEMENT accept-unmasked-frames (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It configures the initial size of the buffer used by the HTTP decoder when processing 
    incoming requests. The default value is 128 bytes, but you can adjust it to potentially 
    improve performance when dealing with large headers or requests by setting it to a more 
    appropriate size.
-->
<!ELEMENT decoder-initial-buffer-size (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    This allows you to specify whether the server should support per-frame WebSocket compression. 
    The default value is true.
-->
<!ELEMENT per-frame-web-socket-compression-supported (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls whether the server supports per-message WebSocket compression, which is a technique 
    to reduce the size of messages sent over a WebSocket connection. The default value is true.
-->
<!ELEMENT per-message-web-socket-compression-supported (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to configure the compression level for WebSocket connections. It's a value 
    between 1 and 9, where higher values mean more compression but potentially slower performance, 
    while lower values mean less compression but potentially faster performance. 
    The default level is 6.
-->
<!ELEMENT web-socket-compression-level (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It is used to configure various aspects of an HTTP server, including WebSocket behavior. 
    The webSocketServer**NoContextTakeover** option, when set within HttpServerOptions, determines 
    whether the server will accept the server_no_context_takeover parameter in the per-message 
    deflate extension offered by the client during WebSocket connections.
-->
<!ELEMENT web-socket-preferred-client-no-context (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It allows you to configure WebSocket behavior, including the handling of server_no_context_takeover 
    parameter in per-message deflate compression. Setting this attribute to true enables the server
    to accept this parameter, indicating it won't maintain a context for deflate compression across 
    messages. This essentially allows for more efficient, albeit potentially less performant in some 
    cases, WebSocket communication.
-->
<!ELEMENT web-socket-allow-server-no-context (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It is used to configure how long the server waits for a WebSocket to close after receiving a 
    close frame from the client. Specifically, it sets the duration for the server to wait before 
    forcibly closing the underlying TCP connection. A value of 0 will close the connection immediately, 
    while a negative value disables the timeout.
-->
<!ELEMENT web-socket-closing-timeout (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It includes a tracingPolicy setting to control how tracing is handled for HTTP requests. 
    The TracingPolicy enum has three options:
    1. ALWAYS - Creates a new trace or reuses an existing one. (default)
    2. IGNORE - Disables tracing for that server.
    3. PROPAGATE - propagates an existing trace if one is present
-->
<!ELEMENT tracing-policy (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It controls whether write handlers for server WebSockets are registered by default. 
    When set to true, the server will register handlers that allow writing data to the 
    WebSocket connection. When set to false (the default), no write handlers are registered, 
    and you'll need to explicitly register them to send data to the WebSocket.
-->
<!ELEMENT register-web-socket-write-handlers (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Set the max number of RST frame allowed per time window, this is used to prevent HTTP/2 RST 
    frame flood DDOS attacks.
-->
<!ELEMENT http2-rst-flood-max-rst-frame-per-window (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It defines the duration of the time window used for detecting and mitigating HTTP/2 RST 
    frame floods. This setting, along with http2MaxRstFramePerWindow, helps prevent 
    denial-of-service attacks that exploit the sending of excessive RST_STREAM frames. 
    The default value is 30 seconds.
-->
<!ELEMENT http2-rst-flood-window-duration (#PCDATA)>

<!ELEMENT cross-origin (allowed-headers|allowed-methods)*>

<!--- 
    List of headers that are allowed by this Vert.x http server.
-->
<!ELEMENT allowed-headers (allowed-header)*>

<!--- Put your DTDDoc comment here. -->
<!ELEMENT allowed-header (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    List of http methods that are suported by this Vert.x http server.
-->
<!ELEMENT allowed-methods (allowed-method)*>

<!--- Put your DTDDoc comment here. -->
<!ELEMENT allowed-method (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Key or trust store options configuring private key and/or certificates based on KeyStore.
    When used as a key store, it should point to a store containing a private key and its certificate.
-->
<!ELEMENT keystore-config (store-name|store-password)*>

<!--- 
    Name of the key store. A file with that name must exist in in the classpath.
    The prefer type is PKCS.
-->
<!ELEMENT store-name EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Password to read the key store file.
-->
<!ELEMENT store-password EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Key or trust store options configuring private key and/or certificates based on KeyStore.
    When used as a trust store, it should point to a store containing a list of trusted certificates.
-->
<!ELEMENT truststore-config (store-name|store-password)*>

<!--- 
    Name of the trust store. A file with that name must exist in in the classpath.
    The prefer type is PKCS.
-->
<!ELEMENT store-name EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Password to read the trust store file.
-->
<!ELEMENT store-password EMPTY>

<!--- 
    A path prefix in a URL that identifies a specific web application deployed on a server.
    It's essentially the "folder" or "namespace" within the server where your application's 
    resources reside.
-->
<!ELEMENT context-root (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    It records all requests processed by an HTTP server. These logs contain valuable information
    such as timestamps, IP addresses, requested URLs, and response codes, which can be used for
    troubleshooting, security monitoring, and analyzing website usage patterns.
-->
<!ELEMENT access-log (log-format|route)*>

<!--- 
    The access log format.
    Must be a sub-class of "io.vertx.ext.web.handler.LoggerFormatter".
-->
<!ELEMENT log-format (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    Define the comma separated path(s) for which access log will be enabled.
-->
<!ELEMENT route (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    A security constraint is used to define the access privileges to a collection of 
    resources using their URL mapping.
-->
<!ELEMENT security-constraint (auth-handler|auth-constraint)*>

<!--- The custom authorization handler -->
<!ELEMENT auth-handler EMPTY>

<!--- 
    Specifies whether authentication is to be used and names the roles authorized to perform 
    the constrained requests.
-->
<!ELEMENT auth-constraint (auth-type|url-patterns)*>

<!--- 
    Custom auth type.
    NO_AUTH is a special type of auth that indicates that authorization will be disabled for
    certain set of urls as specified in the "url-patterns* section.
-->
<!ELEMENT auth-type (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    The url patterns.
-->
<!ELEMENT url-patterns (url-pattern)*>

<!--- Add multiple urls. -->
<!ELEMENT url-pattern (#PCDATA)>

<!--- 
    In Vert.x Web, a route defines a path and associated handler(s) for processing HTTP requests. 
    Routers manage these routes, directing requests to the appropriate handler based on criteria 
    like the HTTP method (GET, POST, etc.), path, or regular expression. Failure handlers are used
    to deal with errors during request processing
    This section contains the file that holds all the routing path and their corresponding handlers.
    The presence of this file is mandatory.
-->
<!ELEMENT routing-config (#PCDATA)>
